00:06:31.559 --> 00:06:34.559
All right, composable data systems.

00:06:34.559 --> 00:06:42.559
Last year at VLDB, I collaborated with fine folks at Meta to write this paper called

00:06:42.559 --> 00:06:46.559
The Composable Data Management System Manifesto.

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:48.559
It's a great paper.

00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:55.559
I want to help you in this talk by presenting some of the key ideas from the paper and why

00:06:55.559 --> 00:06:57.559
they matter.

00:06:57.559 --> 00:06:59.559
I do recommend that you check out this paper.

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:03.559
I think it's really well written.

00:07:03.559 --> 00:07:09.559
The Meta folks did most of the writing, but it's very well written and I think lays out

00:07:09.559 --> 00:07:15.559
a really compelling vision for where things are going.

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:18.559
What is a composable data system?

00:07:18.559 --> 00:07:24.559
The way that I think about this is that we are building systems based on open standards

00:07:24.559 --> 00:07:26.559
and protocols.

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:31.559
We're designing for modularity, reuse, and interoperability with other systems that share

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:35.559
those common interfaces in open standards and protocols.

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:42.559
In particular, we're resisting this idea of vertical integration where every layer of

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:45.559
your system is bespoke and you build it yourself.

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:49.559
It's this homespun thing where you build everything top to bottom.

00:07:49.559 --> 00:07:54.559
It does create more work in some ways because you have to deal with coordination and open

00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:56.559
source diplomacy.

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:00.559
You have to think about moving along these different pieces that you share governance

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:04.559
and you share ownership with other developers and people who are working on different layers

00:08:04.559 --> 00:08:07.559
of the stack.

00:08:07.559 --> 00:08:12.559
The hope is that over time that each of the component pieces that we use to build these

00:08:12.559 --> 00:08:19.559
systems become so much better, easier to use, faster, more interoperable, and that you end

00:08:19.559 --> 00:08:28.559
up creating a solution that is a lot more future-proof and delivers better results over

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:30.559
time.

00:08:30.559 --> 00:08:38.559
It's a little bit painful because you have to go through the painful growing pains of

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:42.559
creating these new systems and making them all work together as well as negotiating with

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:46.559
all of the open source developers that are involved in these projects.

00:08:46.559 --> 00:08:51.559
The way that it was put in the words in the paper is that we envision by decomposing data

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:57.559
management systems into a more modular stack of reusable components, the development of

00:08:57.559 --> 00:09:01.559
engines can be streamlined while reducing maintenance costs and ultimately providing

00:09:01.559 --> 00:09:05.559
a more consistent user experience.

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:11.559
By clearly outlining APIs and encapsulating responsibilities, data management software

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:16.559
could more easily be adapted, for example, to leverage novel devices and accelerators

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:19.559
as the underlying hardware evolves.

00:09:19.559 --> 00:09:23.559
That was one of the reasons why we founded Voltron Data.

00:09:23.559 --> 00:09:29.559
We observed that it's hard for people to take advantage of GPUs to accelerate their systems.

00:09:29.559 --> 00:09:35.559
We also saw that there's many new hardware companies creating new types of hardware.

00:09:35.559 --> 00:09:40.559
We need to make a corresponding investment in the software layer to make it easier to

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:45.559
take advantage of new developments in hardware, whether that's faster computing, faster

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:48.559
networking, faster storage.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:52.559
Ideally, from the standpoint of you as a user, you just want to be able to write Python code

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:56.559
and as the hardware improves, all your software gets faster and you don't have to think about

00:09:56.559 --> 00:10:00.559
the messy details of, well, how do I take advantage of this bleeding edge development

00:10:00.559 --> 00:10:04.559
in computing hardware?

00:10:04.559 --> 00:10:10.559
The hope is that by relying on a modular stack that reuses execution engines, language front-ends,

00:10:10.559 --> 00:10:16.559
the data systems can provide a more consistent experience and semantics to users from

00:10:16.559 --> 00:10:20.559
transactional to analytic systems, stream processing to machine learning workloads.

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:24.559
That sounds very nice in principle.

00:10:24.559 --> 00:10:28.559
One question people have had is, why is this happening now?

00:10:28.559 --> 00:10:32.559
Why is it happening in the 2020s?

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:36.559
Why didn't this happen in the 2010s or even earlier?

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:40.559
It helps to go back and think about the generational eras of big data technology going back to the

00:10:40.559 --> 00:10:46.559
original Google MapReduce paper in the mid-2000s.

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:52.559
The clone of Google MapReduce and Google File System as HDFS and Apache Hadoop,

00:10:52.559 --> 00:10:58.559
that was the first release of Hadoop from Yahoo was in 2006.

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:04.559
The MapReduce paper popularized this idea of disaggregated storage and compute.

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:08.559
You have a big distributed file system, you have all of your data sets live as files in that file

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:14.559
system, and then you have a bunch of compute engines that can process on those files.

00:11:14.559 --> 00:11:20.559
You process files in, the systems write files out back into that distributed file system.

00:11:20.559 --> 00:11:26.559
But what this created was this collection of monolithic vertically integrated systems

00:11:26.559 --> 00:11:30.559
that were part of the Hadoop ecosystem.

00:11:30.559 --> 00:11:34.559
Just getting these components to a place where they were viable and you could use them to

00:11:34.559 --> 00:11:40.559
productively work was hard enough.

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:46.559
Thinking about a hierarchy of needs thing, thinking about how we could modularize components

00:11:46.559 --> 00:11:52.559
of those systems and reuse large pieces of software between those systems,

00:11:52.559 --> 00:11:58.559
that was pie-in-the-sky thinking back in the late 2000s, early 2010s.

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:04.559
But there was a big shift in the 2010s where a particular large software vendor shifted from

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:08.559
selling proprietary vertically integrated software components to delivery of services in a cloud

00:12:08.559 --> 00:12:14.559
environment.

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:20.559
That also led to an emergence of open source standards, file formats like Parquet,

00:12:20.559 --> 00:12:26.559
as well as there was major progress in computing, networking, and storage.

00:12:26.559 --> 00:12:32.559
Disk drives got a lot faster, networking got a lot faster, processor units.

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:38.559
In GPUs a little bit, but in GPUs it's continued to go off to the moon

00:12:38.559 --> 00:12:44.559
as Moore's Law has continued in more specialized processor chips.

00:12:48.559 --> 00:12:54.559
Through that period, as open standards began to emerge, we started thinking about

00:12:54.559 --> 00:13:00.559
how we could create technologies that would help better take advantage

00:13:00.559 --> 00:13:06.559
of the innovation in the hardware and the hardware layer.

00:13:06.559 --> 00:13:12.559
That has led us in this current era to think about re-architecting all of our systems

00:13:12.559 --> 00:13:18.559
on interoperable standards that will enable us to get much better performance

00:13:18.559 --> 00:13:24.559
and efficiency across a heterogeneous application stack that's doing a mixture

00:13:24.559 --> 00:13:30.559
of ML, feature engineering, machine learning training, and AI inference.

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:36.559
We've had this emergence of new standards for composability, which I will talk about.

00:13:36.559 --> 00:13:42.559
We're seeing simultaneously an emergence of new systems which are built to be

00:13:42.559 --> 00:13:48.559
composable from the ground up, as well as retrofitting existing pieces

00:13:48.559 --> 00:13:54.559
of systems with new components which are created with this new composable mindset.

00:13:56.559 --> 00:14:02.559
Back to the paper, we foresee that for composability it's going to cause

00:14:02.559 --> 00:14:08.559
another major disruption to how data management systems are designed.

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:14.559
We foresee that monolithic systems will become obsolete and give space

00:14:14.559 --> 00:14:20.559
for new ideas.

00:14:20.559 --> 00:14:26.559
I was working with the Hadoop ecosystem at the time.

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:32.559
I was trying to socialize these ideas with the data science community.

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:38.559
This was my first talk at the New York R Conference in 2015.

00:14:38.559 --> 00:14:44.559
There wasn't a lot of cross-pollination between the data science world

00:14:44.559 --> 00:14:50.559
and the big data world.

00:14:50.559 --> 00:14:56.559
These were ideas from the big data world that we were trying to socialize

00:14:56.559 --> 00:15:02.559
in the data science community.

00:15:02.559 --> 00:15:08.559
The core idea of this paper is that we've made all of this progress

00:15:08.559 --> 00:15:14.559
in big data systems with impressive scalability, but few of the performance

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:20.559
benchmarks evaluate their absolute.

00:15:20.559 --> 00:15:26.559
They look just at scalability but without evaluating their absolute performance.

00:15:26.559 --> 00:15:32.559
In this paper, they introduce a metric called cost.

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:38.559
It's the configuration that outperforms a single thread to try to measure

00:15:38.559 --> 00:15:44.559
the amount of overhead that is introduced into a distributed system

00:15:44.559 --> 00:15:50.559
by enabling it to scale.

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:56.559
Over the last several years, we've focused work in several key areas.

00:15:58.559 --> 00:16:04.559
Firstly, in protocols, mainly Apache Aero and things related to Apache Aero.

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:10.559
We have a new collection of modular engines which are helping accelerate

00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:16.559
systems, either through new systems which are based on those engines

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:22.559
or retrofitted.

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:30.559
There's a lot of other stuff that isn't in this picture,

00:16:30.559 --> 00:16:36.559
in distributed computing, ETL modeling, workflow and infrastructure orchestration.

00:16:36.559 --> 00:16:42.559
I'm sure there's a lot of talks at this conference

00:16:42.559 --> 00:16:48.559
and a lot of involvement in this was helping create the Apache Aero project.

00:16:48.559 --> 00:16:54.559
We realized in the mid-2010s that we needed to create a cross-language

00:16:54.559 --> 00:17:00.559
fast memory format which could be used for fast in-memory computing

00:17:00.559 --> 00:17:06.560
as well as fast data interchange across disparate systems.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:12.560
We started imagining what if we had this shared data science run time,

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:18.560
a set of libraries and computational systems that we could use interchangeably

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:24.560
across programming languages.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:30.560
It didn't matter which language front-end you're using, what programming language.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:36.560
At the same time, in the database world,

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:42.560
there was also a gnashing of teeth around this problem

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:48.560
of how inefficient it is to import and export data from databases.

