00:22:06.560 --> 00:22:10.560
and we can optimize that substrate plan

00:22:10.560 --> 00:22:14.560
and then the execution engine can take that plan

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:18.560
and turn that into a physical execution plan

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:22.560
that is sent off to the cluster to be executed.

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:30.560
We also retrofit existing popular query engines

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:34.560
with these new modular accelerators.

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:38.560
Three of them that you can get access to

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:42.560
or you can look at or contribute to right now.

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:46.560
One is Prestissimo, which is retrofitting PrestoDB,

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:50.560
I should clarify, not Trino, with Velox.

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:54.560
There's Comet, which has been just donated

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:58.560
into the DataFusion project from Apple,

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:02.560
which is accelerating Spark with DataFusion.

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:06.560
There's also Apache Gluten, part of the Apache Incubator,

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:10.560
which is accelerating Spark with Velox.

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:14.560
Eventually we'll have DataFusion and Presto

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:18.560
and probably every combination of modular accelerators

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:22.560
in our query engine projects.

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:26.560
All of this begins to pose the question of

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:30.560
why as a user should I be locked into using

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:34.560
a particular full-stack query engine like Spark or Presto?

00:23:34.560 --> 00:23:38.560
The cost, performance, and latency

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:42.560
of these different systems varies greatly.

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:46.560
We can do a lot with DuckDB.

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:50.560
But when you have an actual big problem

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:54.560
that's too big for DuckDB,

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:58.560
you want to be able to transition gracefully

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:02.560
to using that larger scalable execution engine.

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:06.560
Of course, last year at Data Council

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:10.560
we had Jordan Tagani on the stage in a duck costume

00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:14.560
talking about how big data is dead.

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:18.560
Big data still is big data. Big data does still exist.

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:22.560
I believe that we should be able to gracefully transition

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:26.560
from working at the single machine,

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:30.560
could be a large single machine, but the small scale

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:34.560
to a large scalable data processing engine

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:38.560
without as much pain and suffering.

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:42.560
This isn't that easy, though, in part because

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:46.560
it advertises just standard SQL.

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:50.560
Because SQL dialects, while SQL is a standard,

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:54.560
in practice SQL dialects are non-portable

00:24:54.560 --> 00:24:58.560
and they feature a wide spectrum of different features.

00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:02.560
There's a tool like SQLGLOT, which is amazing,

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:06.560
which helps with transpiling and converting from one SQL dialect

00:25:06.560 --> 00:25:10.560
to another, but this does create a problem.

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:14.560
You have to solve this problem because if you have a mountain

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:18.560
of existing SQL queries and you want to migrate them

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:22.560
to use a different data processing engine,

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:26.560
you have to rewrite all those queries and deal with all the quirky edge cases

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:30.560
of type coalescing, conversion, and whatnot.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:34.560
Knowing which engine to use in every scenario is non-trivial

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:38.560
and may not always be obvious.

00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:42.560
A few years ago in CIDR 2021,

00:25:42.560 --> 00:25:46.560
folks at Microsoft approached this problem from the standpoint

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:50.560
of the Azure data platform to say,

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:54.560
could we create a unified API for interacting with all these different database engines

00:25:54.560 --> 00:25:58.560
that we have available in the Azure platform and intelligently choose

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:02.560
which one to use based on the type of workload,

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:06.560
like how big the data set is, what statistics we have about the data,

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:10.560
performance, good total cost of ownership for the query.

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:14.560
They described a research project that they did called Magpie

00:26:14.560 --> 00:26:18.560
where they created a pandas-like data frame API.

00:26:18.560 --> 00:26:22.560
They have a compiler and optimizer at the middle.

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:26.560
They have a common data layer, which is based on Arrow,

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:30.560
that provides for a distributed data fabric to coordinate

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:34.560
these different execution engines within the Azure platform.

00:26:34.560 --> 00:26:38.560
These are the different backends that are available in Azure.

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:42.560
I love this idea and I would really like to help it become

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:46.560
more mainstream and a reality for data engineers everywhere.

00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:50.560
A project that I've been involved in,

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:54.560
I started about nine, almost 10 years ago,

00:26:54.560 --> 00:26:58.560
and that we've been putting a lot of resources into is the IBIS project in Python,

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:02.560
which had been an effort to harmonize the best features of modern SQL

00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:06.560
with Python's fluent data frame APIs.

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:10.560
We also wanted in IBIS to fix shortcomings in the pandas API

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:14.560
and make things that are hard to do with pandas a lot easier to do with IBIS,

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:18.560
so we made a deliberate choice to depart from the pandas API.

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:22.560
We wanted to make it easy to build complex,

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:26.560
large analytical SQL queries by using the benefits of a modern

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:30.560
programming language, functions and parameters and things like that,

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:34.560
things that don't exist in SQL.

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:38.560
Over the years, we've been really focused on portability and compatibility

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:42.560
across a wide spectrum of engines who now support over 20 backends

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:46.560
to provide a unified API that could be the basis

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:50.560
of building a multi-engine data stack.

00:27:50.560 --> 00:27:54.560
IBIS code, this produces a pretty complex SQL query

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:58.560
and everything is based on pipe-like

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:02.560
sequences of methods that compose with each other

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:06.560
to create complex expressions.

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:10.560
One of the workflows that we hear a lot of pain points about

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:14.560
and people wanting to work in this ecosystem

00:28:14.560 --> 00:28:18.560
and to create a composable data stack is how to go from

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:22.560
dev to prod.

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:26.560
Nobody wants to burn a ton of snowflake credits while they're developing

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:30.560
and the ideal scenario would be to be able to develop,

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:34.560
build your model, do all of your development locally on your laptop

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:38.560
with DuckDB and whenever you're ready to go into prod

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:42.560
in Spark SQL or BigQuery or Snowflake,

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:46.560
then it's about as easy as flipping the switch.

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:50.560
Run this workflow but in Snowflake and to not have to rewrite all of your queries.

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:54.560
That's one of the key things that we're trying to facilitate

00:28:54.560 --> 00:28:58.560
in this project.

00:28:58.560 --> 00:29:02.560
One of the reasons why this is so important is because

00:29:02.560 --> 00:29:06.560
at truly large-scale workloads, this is benchmarks that were just published

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:10.560
by Voltron Data last week at GTC.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:14.560
We showed that when you have a specialized cluster of GPUs,

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:18.560
so this is comparing Spark SQL and EMR

00:29:18.560 --> 00:29:22.560
compared with a 80-node, 80-GPU on-prem cluster

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:26.560
with Finaband and NVLink and all the bells and whistles.

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:30.560
If you have a truly large-scale workload at 10 terabyte and up

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:34.560
and you're willing to make an investment in hardware or to rent hardware

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:38.560
to work at that scale, you can get some truly amazing performance

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:42.560
with the hardware that's available today.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:46.560
We want to facilitate taking advantage of hardware acceleration

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:50.560
in really large-scale workloads.

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:54.560
It's a pain to work at small-scale, but whenever you're working

00:29:54.560 --> 00:29:58.560
at very large-scale queries, you have to work in a completely different way.

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:02.560
That's very painful for the user.

00:30:02.560 --> 00:30:06.560
If you're a large company and you have a lot of workloads

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:10.560
that are going into your GPU cluster,

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:14.560
which you want to reserve only for your large-scale workloads,

00:30:14.560 --> 00:30:18.560
you don't want to clog with a bunch of small-scale queries.

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:22.560
I see all of these technologies building up

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:26.560
to make that possible.

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:30.560
I really aspire to help us

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:34.560
create the reality of a multi-engine, multi-engine data stack

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:38.560
to have execution engines available that are tailored for different data scales

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:42.560
so that when you're below a terabyte, you can use DuckDB, Data Fusion,

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:46.560
things that run on your laptop,

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:50.560
and that those larger scales that you can transition to using Spark

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:54.560
or more specialized tools at a much larger scale,

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:58.560
a lot more gracefully and for you as a user,

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:02.560
a lot more productivity.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:06.560
I'm pretty excited about these kind of new portable language

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:10.560
front-end projects.

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:14.560
I didn't have time to talk about it in this talk,

00:31:14.560 --> 00:31:18.560
but something really exciting is a whole new programming language

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:22.560
for analytical queries that I encourage you to check out.

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:26.560
Another project, I think it's called PRQL,

00:31:26.560 --> 00:31:30.560
Pipeline Relational Query Language,

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:34.560
another effort to build a better SQL.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:38.560
Particularly as these execution components standardize,

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:42.560
I think a lot of the work in data systems

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:46.560
is making it easier to orchestrate systems,

00:31:46.560 --> 00:31:50.560
write queries, execute them portably across these different environments.

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:54.560
Now, almost eight years into Arrow,

00:31:54.560 --> 00:31:58.560
almost nine years since we started conceiving and putting together the project,

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:02.560
it's great that Arrow is becoming the de facto standard

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:06.560
for how we build APIs and how we connect systems together.

00:32:06.560 --> 00:32:10.560
I think that bodes well for even better performance

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:14.560
So with that, I'm sure you're all hungry, ready for lunch,

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:18.560
but I think I have time for a few questions,

00:32:18.560 --> 00:32:22.560
and I appreciate your attention. Thanks.

